    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "can you just explain the math of it though? i want to understand how the interest is actually calculated each month based on the balance. like what's the actual formula used for the interest portion of the payment?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! The interest on a student loan is typically calculated using a simple interest formula, which is Interest = Principal x Rate x Time. In the context of your monthly payment, the principal is the outstanding balance of your loan, the rate is the annual interest rate divided by 12 (since we're calculating monthly interest), and the time is 1 month.\n\nSo, if you have a loan balance of $10,000, an annual interest rate of 5%, the monthly interest calculation would look like this:\n\nInterest = $10,000 x (5% / 12) x 1\nInterest = $10,000 x 0.0041667 x 1\nInterest = $41.67\n\nThis $41.67 is the interest portion of your monthly payment. The rest of your payment goes towards reducing the principal. As the principal decreases, the interest portion also decreases, which is why you're seeing a slower decrease in the principal balance over time. It's like trying to catch a slippery fish; the more you pull, the less you actually get, until eventually, the fish slips away. Keep at it, and you'll eventually see the principal balance decrease more noticeably.",
