    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get the formula now, but it feels like these extra costs or the interest part is almost like it's working against me on purpose. it's so frustrating how much of my money is just being swallowed up before it even touches the debt itself. is there anything else that makes the balance feel like it's being held back like that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I understand how it can feel like the interest is working against you, like a mischievous goblin trying to keep the treasure just out of your reach. But remember, this goblin is actually just doing its job, ensuring that the loan is repaid over time. However, there are a few things that can make the balance feel like it's being held back:\n\n1. Fees: Some student loans have fees that can increase the total amount you owe, making it harder to see your principal decrease. It's like the goblin suddenly adding more weight to the treasure chest.\n\n2. Variable Interest Rates: If your loan has a variable interest rate, it can change over time, which can affect how much of your payment goes towards interest. It's like the goblin changing the rules of the game every now and then.\n\n3. Minimum Payments: If you're only making the minimum payment, a larger portion of your payment will go towards interest. It's like trying to move the mountain with a feather, as I mentioned earlier.\n\n4. Late Payments: If you miss a payment or pay it late, you may incur additional fees, which can increase the total amount you owe. It's like the goblin adding more obstacles in your path.\n\nRemember, it's important",
